canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> before being killed by police following a car chase.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/rcmp-say-in-excess-of-19-victims-in-n-s-rampage-1.4903398|title=RCMP say 'in excess of 19 victims' in N.S. rampage|date=2020-04-20|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the evening of April 19 and ended when Wortman was pronounced dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP).\n \nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=At Least 16 Killed in Nova Scotia Shooting, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside a home, but not the suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe investigation overnight led police to many crime scenes that were scattered over at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> At around 8:00 a.m. on April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation. Residents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of the town was evacuated.<ref name=nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman/><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Three buildings and two cars were reported burning, which required a firefighter response.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman/><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 17 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman, was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m. on April 19.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, Wortman was sighted in [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /> In the same time-frame, the public were warned that he might be [[police impersonation|posing as an RCMP officer]] and operating a vehicle made to look like an RCMP vehicle,<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> and that he was travelling on Highway 4 near [[Glenholme]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Residents were urged to avoid the area.<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police asked the public to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, they said he switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /> The [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting.<ref name=\"CBC\" />\n\n== Victims ==\nAt least 19 people were killed (excluding Worthman), one of them a 23-year veteran RCMP officer, Constable Heidi Stevenson. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> At least one other person was also injured.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC-52346447\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|date=20 April 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420075915/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"BBC-52346447\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" />\n\n== Perpetrator ==\nThe RCMP named Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area on April 19 after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=2020-04-19|website=Atlantic|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Wortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, having a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two police cruisers he bought near his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with alcoholism, and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=After Nova Scotia Shooting, Families Mourn as Police Seek a Motive|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=Atlantic|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Sparkle1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "Lorna Magara", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan educator and administrator}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Lorna Magara\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| honorific_prefix = \n| birth_name  = Lorna Magara\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Ugandan \n| alma_mater  ='''[[Makerere University]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Bachelor of Arts]] with [[Education]])}}<br/>'''[[Uganda Christian University]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Master of Arts]] in [[Leadership|Organizational Leadership and Management]])}}<br/>'''Institute of National Transformation'''<br/>{{small|(Oak Seed Executive Leadership Course)}}<br/>'''Sundoulos African Leadership Training Institute'''<br/>{{small|(Certificate of Servant Leadership)}}<br/>'''Christian Education, Europe'''<br/>{{small|(International Certificate of Christian Education)}}\n| occupation = Educator, [[academic]], and management professional\n| years_active = 1989 - present\n| home_town    = \n| spouse       = <small>Dr. James Magara</small>\n| title        = [[Chairperson]] of [[Makerere University|Makerere University Council]]\n}}\n'''Lorna Magara''' is the first woman to be elected [[chairperson]] of the [[Makerere University|Makerere University Council]], since the founding of the university in 1922. She was elected to a renewable four-year term, effective 20 December 2018. The Council is a 27-member body that serves as the supreme governing organ of Uganda's largest and oldest [[public university]].<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|date=22 December 2018 |url=https://www.softpower.ug/lorna-magara-elected-first-female-chairperson-of-makerere-university-council/ |title=Lorna Magara Elected First Female Chairperson Of Makerere University Council | publisher=Soft Power Uganda |access-date=23 December 2018 |author=Paul Ampurire |location=Kampala}}</ref><ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|title=Magara is new Makerere council chairperson |access-date=23 December 2018 |date=21 December 2018 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Magara-new-Makerere-council-chairperson/688334-4904550-9oglisz/index.html | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |first=Damali |last=Mukhaye | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n== Background and education ==\nShe was born to Hezron<ref name=\"FamR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.freewebhostinguganda.com/ugandapressreview/kakuyo-the-fallen-hero-who-left-an-indelible-legacy/ |title=Kakuyo the fallen hero who left an indelible legacy |publisher=Uganda Press REVIEW\u00ae | date=22 February 2019 |access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref> and Catherine Kakuyo in 1966<ref name=\"WoR\">{{cite web| newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | date=30 March 2019 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/Full-Woman/Lorna-Magara-First-woman-at-the-helm-of-Makerere/689842-5048008-xbb28y/index.html |title=Lorna Magara: First woman at the helm of Makerere\u2019s governing |access-date=31 March 2019 | first=Eric |last=Kyama |location=Kampala}}</ref> and spent most of her childhood in [[Jinja, Uganda|Jinja]]. After attending Victoria and Berkley primary schools, both in eastern Uganda, for her primary education, she then joined [[Gayaza High School]] for all six years of her secondary education<ref name=\"WoR\"/> \nMs Magara was admitted to [[Makerere University]] in 1985, where she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree with a concurrent [[Education|Diploma in Education]], in 1988.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web|date=22 December 2018 |access-date=23 December 2018 |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |author=New Vision Staff |url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1491649/magara-takes-makerere-council |title=Magara Takes Over Makerere Council, But Who Is She? |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nHer second degree is a [[Master of Arts]] in [[Leadership|Organizational Leadership and Management]], awarded by [[Uganda Christian University]], in [[Mukono District]]. In addition, she has several certificates in leadership and education from local and international institutions.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the first six years of her career, from 1989 until 1995, Ms Magara was a human resource officer at [[National Social Security Fund (Uganda)|Uganda National Social Security Fund]] (NSSF). In this capacity, she was part of the team that established the training department and manpower planning unit at NSSF.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nAfter that, she went into private consulting and serves as the Director at ''Destiny Consult Limited'', a private consultancy that provided leadership training programs. This phase of her career lasted 12 years, until 2008.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nIn 2008 she became a faculty member at ''African Kingdom Business Forum'' (AKBF), a personnel development consultancy that provides  leadership training programs. She also started working as a member of the faculty at ''Sundolous African Leadership Training Program'' (SALT), another human resources and training consultancy.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nShe is expected to serve a renewable four-year term as Chairperson of Makerere University Council and will be deputized by [[Daniel Kidega]], the former speaker of the [[East African Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"1R\"/><ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==Other considerations==\nMs Magara is the founder and Principal of ''Vine International Christian Academy'', a school with grades from Pre-School to Grade 12, located in Kungu, [[Kira Town|Kira Municipality]], [[Wakiso District]], [[Central Region, Uganda|Buganda Region]], Uganda.<ref name=\"3R\"/><ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|date=23 December 2018 | url=http://vicacademy.org/index.php/about-us |title=About Vine International Christian Academy |access-date=23 December 2018 |   publisher=Vine International Christian Academy |author=Vine International Christian Academy |location=Kira Municipality}}</ref>\n\nShe is a Director at ''Jubilee Dental Limited'', a company that operates three dental clinics in Uganda and one in [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]]. She is the Africa Representative of Accelerated Education Enterprise, Uganda Chapter; Team Leader of Education Accelerators Uganda Limited. She is the Uganda Coordinator for International Certificate for Christian Education.<ref name=\"3R\"/><ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|date=21 December 2018 | url=https://www.independent.co.ug/lorna-magara-voted-new-mak-university-council-chairperson/ |title=Lorna Magara voted new Makerere University Council Chairperson  |newspaper=[[The Independent (Uganda)]] |author=The Independent |access-date=23 December 2018 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLorna Magara is married to Dr. James Magara and the couple has four children between them, three boys and one girl.<ref name=\"WoR\"/> She is also sister to [[Allen Kagina]] , Jocelyn Kyobutungi Rugunda (wife to Uganda's Prime Minister [[Ruhakana Rugunda]] ) as well as Caleb Kakuyo, the former Chief Commercial Officer at the [[National Housing and Construction Company]], among others<ref name=\"FamR\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.mak.ac.ug/ Website of Makerere University]\n* [https://chimpreports.com/lorna-magara-elected-new-chairperson-of-makerere-university-council/ Lorna Magara Elected New Chairperson Of Makerere University Council]\n\n==Succession table as Chairperson of Makerere University Council==\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairperson<br/>[[Makerere University| Makerere University Council]]||before=Dr Charles Wana Etyem<br/>2010 - 2018|after=[[TBD]] (After December 2022)| years='''December 2018 \u2013 December 2022'''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magara, Lorna}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan educators]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women in business]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:Uganda Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gayaza High School]]\n[[Category:People from Kiruhura District]]\n[[Category:People from Western Region, Uganda]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan educator and administrator}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Lorna Magara\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| honorific_prefix = \n| birth_name  = Lorna Magara\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Ugandan \n| alma_mater  ='''[[Makerere University]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Bachelor of Arts]] with [[Education]])}}<br/>'''[[Uganda Christian University]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Master of Arts]] in [[Leadership|Organizational Leadership and Management]])}}<br/>'''Institute of National Transformation'''<br/>{{small|(Oak Seed Executive Leadership Course)}}<br/>'''Sundoulos African Leadership Training Institute'''<br/>{{small|(Certificate of Servant Leadership)}}<br/>'''Christian Education, Europe'''<br/>{{small|(International Certificate of Christian Education)}}\n| occupation = Educator, [[academic]], and management professional\n| years_active = 1989 - present\n| home_town    = \n| spouse       = <small>Dr. James Magara</small>\n| title        = [[Chairperson]] of [[Makerere University|Makerere University Council]]\n}}\n'''Lorna Magara''' is the first woman to be elected [[chairperson]] of the [[Makerere University|Makerere University Council]], since the founding of the university in 1922. She was elected to a renewable four-year term, effective 20 December 2018. The Council is a 27-member body that serves as the supreme governing organ of Uganda's largest and oldest [[public university]].<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|date=22 December 2018 |url=https://www.softpower.ug/lorna-magara-elected-first-female-chairperson-of-makerere-university-council/ |title=Lorna Magara Elected First Female Chairperson Of Makerere University Council | publisher=Soft Power Uganda |access-date=23 December 2018 |author=Paul Ampurire |location=Kampala}}</ref><ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|title=Magara is new Makerere council chairperson |access-date=23 December 2018 |date=21 December 2018 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Magara-new-Makerere-council-chairperson/688334-4904550-9oglisz/index.html | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |first=Damali |last=Mukhaye | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n== Background and education ==\nShe was born to Hezron<ref name=\"FamR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.freewebhostinguganda.com/ugandapressreview/kakuyo-the-fallen-hero-who-left-an-indelible-legacy/ |title=Kakuyo the fallen hero who left an indelible legacy |publisher=Uganda Press REVIEW\u00ae | date=22 February 2019 |access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref> and Catherine Kakuyo in 1966<ref name=\"WoR\">{{cite web| newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | date=30 March 2019 | url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/Full-Woman/Lorna-Magara-First-woman-at-the-helm-of-Makerere/689842-5048008-xbb28y/index.html |title=Lorna Magara: First woman at the helm of Makerere\u2019s governing |access-date=31 March 2019 | first=Eric |last=Kyama |location=Kampala}}</ref> and spent most of her childhood in [[Jinja, Uganda|Jinja]]. After attending Victoria and Berkley primary schools, both in eastern Uganda, for her primary education, she then joined [[Gayaza High School]] for all six years of her secondary education<ref name=\"WoR\"/> \nMs Magara was admitted to [[Makerere University]] in 1985, where she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree with a concurrent [[Education|Diploma in Education]], in 1988.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web|date=22 December 2018 |access-date=23 December 2018 |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |author=New Vision Staff |url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1491649/magara-takes-makerere-council |title=Magara Takes Over Makerere Council, But Who Is She? |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nHer second degree is a [[Master of Arts]] in [[Leadership|Organizational Leadership and Management]], awarded by [[Uganda Christian University]], in [[Mukono District]]. In addition, she has several certificates in leadership and education from local and international institutions.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the first six years of her career, from 1989 until 1995, Ms Magara was a human resource officer at [[National Social Security Fund (Uganda)|Uganda National Social Security Fund]] (NSSF). In this capacity, she was part of the team that established the training department and manpower planning unit at NSSF.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nAfter that, she went into private consulting and serves as the Director at ''Destiny Consult Limited'', a private consultancy that provided leadership training programs. This phase of her career lasted 12 years, until 2008.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nIn 2008 she became a faculty member at ''African Kingdom Business Forum'' (AKBF), a personnel development consultancy that provides  leadership training programs. She also started working as a member of the faculty at ''Sundolous African Leadership Training Program'' (SALT), another human resources and training consultancy.<ref name=\"3R\"/>\n\nShe is expected to serve a renewable four-year term as Chairperson of Makerere University Council and will be deputized by [[Daniel Kidega]], the former speaker of the [[East African Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"1R\"/><ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==Other considerations==\nMs Magara is the founder and Principal of ''Vine International Christian Academy'', a school with grades from Pre-School to Grade 12, located in Kungu, [[Kira Town|Kira Municipality]], [[Wakiso District]], [[Central Region, Uganda|Buganda Region]], Uganda.<ref name=\"3R\"/><ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|date=23 December 2018 | url=http://vicacademy.org/index.php/about-us |title=About Vine International Christian Academy |access-date=23 December 2018 |   publisher=Vine International Christian Academy |author=Vine International Christian Academy |location=Kira Municipality}}</ref>\n\nShe is a Director at ''Jubilee Dental Limited'', a company that operates three dental clinics in Uganda and one in [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]]. She is the Africa Representative of Accelerated Education Enterprise, Uganda Chapter; Team Leader of Education Accelerators Uganda Limited. She is the Uganda Coordinator for International Certificate for Christian Education.<ref name=\"3R\"/><ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|date=21 December 2018 | url=https://www.independent.co.ug/lorna-magara-voted-new-mak-university-council-chairperson/ |title=Lorna Magara voted new Makerere University Council Chairperson  |newspaper=[[The Independent (Uganda)]] |author=The Independent |access-date=23 December 2018 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLorna Magara is married to Dr. James Magara and the couple has four children between them, three boys and one girl.<ref name=\"WoR\"/> She is also sister to [[Allen Kagina]] , Jocelyn Kyobutungi Rugunda (wife to Uganda's Prime Minister [[Ruhakana Rugunda]] ) as well as Caleb Kakuyo, the former Chief Commercial Officer at the [[National Housing and Construction Company]], among others<ref name=\"FamR\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.mak.ac.ug/ Website of Makerere University]\n* [https://chimpreports.com/lorna-magara-elected-new-chairperson-of-makerere-university-council/ Lorna Magara Elected New Chairperson Of Makerere University Council]\n\n==Succession table as Chairperson of Makerere University Council==\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairperson<br/>[[Makerere University| Makerere University Council]]||before=Dr Charles Wana Etyem<br/>2010 - 2018|after=[[TBD]] (After December 2022)| years='''December 2018 \u2013 December 2022'''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magara, Lorna}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women]]\n[[Category:Ugandan educators]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women in business]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Catego