{"title_page": "Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Shenstone}}\n{{other people|William Parker}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir William Parker, Bt\n|birth_date=1 January 1743\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|1802|10|31|1743|1|1}}\n|birth_place= Harburn,<ref>[http://www3.sympatico.ca/dljordan/parker-edwards.htm The Parker and Edwards Families]</ref> [[Warwickshire]]\n|death_place= \n|image=Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn.jpg\n|caption=Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|commands= [[Leeward Islands Station]]<br>[[Jamaica Station]]<br>[[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]]\n|branch=  {{navy|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|unit=\n|battles=[[American Revolutionary War]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet''' (1 January 1743 \u2013 31 October 1802), was a British naval commander.\n\n==Naval career==\nWilliam Parker's father, Augustine Parker, had been [[mayor]] of [[Queenborough]], [[Isle of Sheppey]], [[Kent]] and a commander of one of the king's [[yacht]]s.<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21347?docPos=8 Sir William Parker at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> William Parker entered the navy about 1756 and in 1758 was on {{HMS|Centurion|1732|6}} during the [[Siege of Louisbourg (1758)|capture of Louisbourg]] in [[Canada]] and the [[Battle of the Plains of Abraham|capture of Quebec]] the following year.<ref name=odnb/> He was promoted to lieutenant in 1762.<ref name=odnb/> For a time he served off the coast of [[Colony of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]] and was promoted to commander in 1763.<ref name=odnb/> In 1777 he went to the [[West Indies]] where he served under [[John Byron|Byron]].<ref name=odnb/> He served aboard various ships and as commodore and commander-in-chief on the [[Leeward Islands Station]] between 1787 and 1789.<ref name=odnb/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haydn|first1=Joseph|title=The Book of Dignities: Containing Lists of the Official Personages of the British Empire ... from the Earliest Periods to the Present Time ... Together with the Sovereigns and Rulers of Europe, from the Foundation of Their Respective States; the Peerage of England and Great Britain Original 1851 Digitized by the University of Michigan|date=13 Jun 2008|publisher=Longmans, Brown, Green, and Longmans|page=279|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aURnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA272&dq=%22Admiral+William+O%27Bryen+Drury%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref> During the 1790s he served under Admiral [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]].<ref name=odnb/> In 1794 he commanded {{HMS|Audacious|1785|6}} at the Battle of [[The Glorious First of June]] and was promoted to [[Rear-Admiral]].<ref name=odnb/> \n\nAfter service on the [[Jamaica Station]] in 1796,<ref>Cundall, p. xx</ref> he took part under Sir [[John Jervis, 1st Earl of St Vincent|John Jervis]] in the [[Battle of Cape St Vincent (1797)|Battle of Cape St Vincent]] in 1797, where he damaged the 112-gun ship [[HMS San Josef (1797)|''San Josef'']] so badly that Commodore [[Horatio Nelson]] was able to board and capture her with little opposition.<ref name=odnb/> The following year Parker, on blockade duty off [[Cadiz]], bitterly resented that Nelson, junior to himself, was given an independent command in the [[Mediterranean]], but his letters to the Admiralty had no effect.<ref name=odnb/> He ended his career as [[North America and West Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief in North America]] at [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] from 1800, and was recalled for disobeying orders.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924020417527#page/n27/mode/2up|title=Historic Jamaica|first=Frank|last=Cundall|publisher=West India Committee|year=1915}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Sir Richard Bickerton, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Bickerton]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Leeward Islands Station|Commander-in-Chief, Leeward Islands Station]] | years=1787\u20131789}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[John Laforey|Sir John Laforey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Ford (Royal Navy officer)|John Ford]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Jamaica Station|Commander-in-Chief, Jamaica Station]]| years=1796}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Richard Rodney Bligh]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[North America and West Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief, North American Station]]|before=[[George Vandeput]]|after=[[Andrew Mitchell (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Andrew Mitchell]]|years=1800\u20131802}}\n|-\n{{s-reg|gb-bt}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Parker Baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Harburn)''' | years=1797\u20131802 | before= New creation |  after=William George Parker  }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, William}}\n[[Category:1743 births]]\n[[Category:1802 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:People from Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the French and Indian War]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Shenstone}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir William Parker, Bt\n|birth_date=1 January 1743\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|1802|10|31|1743|1|1}}\n|birth_place= Harburn,<ref>[http://www3.sympatico.ca/dljordan/parker-edwards.htm The Parker and Edwards Families]</ref> [[Warwickshire]]\n|death_place= \n|image=Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn.jpg\n|caption=Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet, of Harburn\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|commands= [[Leeward Islands Station]]<br>[[Jamaica Station]]<br>[[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]]\n|branch=  {{navy|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|unit=\n|battles=[[American Revolutionary War]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Sir William Parker, 1st Baronet''' (1 January 1743 \u2013 31 October 1802), was a British naval commander.\n\n==Naval career==\nWilliam Parker's father, Augustine Parker, had been [[mayor]] of [[Queenborough]], [[Isle of Sheppey]], [[Kent]] and a commander of one of the king's [[yacht]]s.<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21347?docPos=8 Sir William Parker at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> William Parker entered the navy about 1756 and in 1758 was on {{HMS|Centurion|1732|6}} during the [[Siege of Louisbourg (1758)|capture of Louisbourg]] in [[Canada]] and the [[Battle of the Plains of Abraham|capture of Quebec]] the following year.<ref name=odnb/> He was promoted to lieutenant in 1762.<ref name=odnb/> For a time he served off the coast of [[Colony of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]] and was promoted to commander in 1763.<ref name=odnb/> In 1777 he went to the [[West Indies]] where he served under [[John Byron|Byron]].<ref name=odnb/> He served aboard various ships and as commodore and commander-in-chief on the [[Leeward Islands Station]] between 1787 and 1789.<ref name=odnb/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Haydn|first1=Joseph|title=The Book of Dignities: Containing Lists of the Official Personages of the British Empire ... from the Earliest Periods to the Present Time ... Together with the Sovereigns and Rulers of Europe, from the Foundation of Their Respective States; the Peerage of England and Great Britain Original 1851 Digitized by the University of Michigan|date=13 Jun 2008|publisher=Longmans, Brown, Green, and Longmans|page=279|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aURnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA272&dq=%22Admiral+William+O%27Bryen+Drury%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref> During the 1790s he served under Admiral [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Lord Howe]].<ref name=odnb/> In 1794 he commanded {{HMS|Audacious|1785|6}} at the Battle of [[The Glorious First of June]] and was promoted to [[Rear-Admiral]].<ref name=odnb/> \n\nAfter service on the [[Jamaica Station]] in 1796,<ref>Cundall, p. xx</ref> he took part under Sir [[John Jervis, 1st Earl of St Vincent|John Jervis]] in the [[Battle of Cape St Vincent (1797)|Battle of Cape St Vincent]] in 1797, where he damaged the 112-gun ship [[HMS San Josef (1797)|''San Josef'']] so badly that Commodore [[Horatio Nelson]] was able to board and capture her with little opposition.<ref name=odnb/> The following year Parker, on blockade duty off [[Cadiz]], bitterly resented that Nelson, junior to himself, was given an independent command in the [[Mediterranean]], but his letters to the Admiralty had no effect.<ref name=odnb/> He ended his career as [[North America and West Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief in North America]] at [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] from 1800, and was recalled for disobeying orders.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924020417527#page/n27/mode/2up|title=Historic Jamaica|first=Frank|last=Cundall|publisher=West India Committee|year=1915}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Sir Richard Bickerton, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Bickerton]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Leeward Islands Station|Commander-in-Chief, Leeward Islands Station]] | years=1787\u20131789}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[John Laforey|Sir John Laforey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Ford (Royal Navy officer)|John Ford]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Jamaica Station|Commander-in-Chief, Jamaica Station]]| years=1796}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Richard Rodney Bligh]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[North America and West Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief, North American Station]]|before=[[George Vandeput]]|after=[[Andrew Mitchell (Royal Navy officer)|Sir Andrew Mitchell]]|years=1800\u20131802}}\n|-\n{{s-reg|gb-bt}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Parker Baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Harburn)''' | years=1797\u20131802 | before= New creation |  after=William George Parker  }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, William}}\n[[Category:1743 births]]\n[[Category:1802 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:People from Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the French and Indian War]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n", "name_user": "Titi Bastia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_William_Parker,_1st_Baronet,_of_Harburn"}
